{
  "doc_id": "19813",
  "text": "The Brightness:Luminance ratio (or Helmholtz-Kohlrausch effect) is a complex effect, mainly comprising the change in perceived brightness of colors/lights of varying dominant wavelength but of the same luminance [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The lowest B:L ratio is for yellow about 575 nm, and the highest ratio is at the spectrum ends (blue and red hues), indicating that B:L ratio is approximately proportional to saturation.",
